that as well.

34:53.191 --> 34:54.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I see.

34:54.993 --> 34:59.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know that a lot of farmers and
businesses
and developers have said that
this rule was

34:59.764 --> 35:01.599 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hugely burdensome to them.

35:01.633 --> 35:07.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Was this an issue primarily of
cost to them,
or confusion about what rules
were covered?

35:07.505 --> 35:09.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What was the issue?

35:09.407 --> 35:13.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIET EILPERIN: It was a
combination of both
the costs that they might have
to incur, but

35:13.244 --> 35:15.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also whether they were permitted
to do something
or not.

35:15.814 --> 35:21.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you had -- one thing that's
difficult
is essentially these activities
were being

35:22.020 --> 35:27.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decided on a case-by-case basis,
and so you
had individual operators,
whether you're talking

35:27.692 --> 35:34.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about someone who is operating a
gravel pit
or trying to expand a parking
lot or do something

35:34.432 --> 35:39.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on his or her ranch -- all of
those folks
were engaged in conversations
with the Environmental

35:39.304 --> 35:42.440 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Protection Agency and the Army
Corps of Engineers.

35:42.474 --> 35:44.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And sometimes the decisions
didn't go the
way they wanted to.

35:44.976 --> 35:47.312 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There were fines imposed on
them.

35:47.345 --> 35:52.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so there were these
long-running disputes
happening across the country
where the federal

35:52.250 --> 35:56.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government was saying, that in
order to protect
these sources of water, they
couldn't do things

35:56.821 --> 35:59.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or had to pay for some of the
actions that
they undertook.

35:59.591 --> 36:03.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I understand a
lot of environmental
groups and some sporting groups
have been

36:03.561 --> 36:05.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very critical of this rollback.

36:05.463 --> 36:07.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is their complaint?

36:07.298 --> 36:11.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIET EILPERIN: Their argument
-- and there
certainly are a lot of them --
is that these

36:11.202 --> 36:16.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
water bodies, though it might be
inconvenient
to have restrictions, were
crucial habitat

36:16.374 --> 36:22.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for everything from waterfowl,
many migratory
birds, aquatic species, as well
as a source

36:22.881 --> 36:25.917 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of drinking water for millions
of Americans.

36:25.950 --> 36:30.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so these groups, primarily
outdoor recreation
groups, as well as many
environmental groups,

36:31.022 --> 36:36.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
worked extensively during the
Obama administration
to get them to finalize this
rule, in the

36:36.294 --> 36:41.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hopes that there would be an
overarching standard
that could be applied across the
country that

36:41.699 --> 36:45.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would provide more stringent
protections for
these streams and wetlands.

36:45.703 --> 36:50.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, with
President Trump's
order, this doesn't immediately
undue the

36:51.009 --> 36:52.077 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rule.

36:52.110 --> 36:53.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, tomorrow, the rule doesn't
disappear,
right?

36:53.845 --> 37:00.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIET EILPERIN: It doesn't,
although the
Sixth Circuit has put a
nationwide stay on

37:00.185 --> 37:04.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the rule, so the rule has not
gone into effect
and will not go into effect.

37:04.689 --> 37:10.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, the order that
President Trump
signed instructs the attorney
general to ask

37:10.462 --> 37:17.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that court to simply hold that
lawsuit in
abeyance, essentially freezing
this rule further,

37:17.902 --> 37:23.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
while the two agencies that are
charged with
overseeing it look at whether
they can undo

37:23.808 --> 37:28.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it, although that again is an
extensive process
and will spur more lawsuits
going forward.

37:28.746 --> 37:33.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Juliet Eilperin
of The Washington Post, thanks
so much.

37:33.451 --> 37:41.593 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JULIET EILPERIN: Thank you.

37:41.626 --> 37:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

37:46.564 --> 37:52.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
documenting the
civil rights movement through
powerful images;

37:52.070 --> 37:55.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and airlifting bison to a new
home.

37:55.039 --> 38:00.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But first:
With stepped-up
enforcement along the
U.S.-Mexican border,

38:00.545 --> 38:05.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is more anxiety among
immigrant communities
that families members with
different status

38:06.017 --> 38:07.819 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
might be separated.

38:07.852 --> 38:12.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In New Mexico, one small
binational community
along the border is working hard
to keep families

38:12.590 --> 38:14.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
connected through schools.

38:14.526 --> 38:19.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From Public Media's Fronteras
desk and PBS
station KRWG, Simon Thompson,
originally from

38:19.864 --> 38:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Australia, brings us this
report.

38:21.666 --> 38:27.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Daylight hasn't
even broken,
but 500 children who live in
Palomas, Mexico,

38:27.772 --> 38:30.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are up and on their way to
school.

38:30.275 --> 38:32.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Their commute is not typical.

38:32.243 --> 38:36.748 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They must first cross the
international border
into the U.S.

38:36.781 --> 38:43.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They show their U.S. passports
and birth certificates.

38:43.421 --> 38:46.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Customs and Immigration
officials inspect
their school bags.

38:46.925 --> 38:52.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then they're bussed to school in
Luna County,
New Mexico.

38:52.764 --> 38:57.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lizett Preciado is a senior at
Deming High
School in Luna County.

38:57.635 --> 39:02.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A U.S. citizen, she's lived in
Palomas with
her parents for seven years.

39:02.540 --> 39:04.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZETT PRECIADO, Student: It was
good to be
able to go to school there.

39:04.442 --> 39:10.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, like, there's more
opportunities to study
and to have a better job in the
future.

39:10.315 --> 39:16.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Lizett and her
family moved
to Palomas from Colorado, after
her mother,

39:16.221 --> 39:20.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rosa Marie, was deported for
being in the
United States illegally.

39:20.258 --> 39:27.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROSA MARIA PRECIADO, Mother
(through translator):
I felt really bad, really badly,
because I

39:27.832 --> 39:32.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have four children who are
citizens of the
United States, and my husband is
a resident.

39:32.637 --> 39:35.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I didn't want to go back to live
in Mexico.

39:35.773 --> 39:39.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know it is my country, but
life in Mexico
in really hard.

39:39.744 --> 39:45.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Preciado and her
husband,
Ramon, makes their living in
Palomas raising

39:45.216 --> 39:46.484 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
goats.

39:46.517 --> 39:51.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ramon still crosses occasionally
back into
the U.S. to work.

39:51.956 --> 39:56.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Preciado says having her
children educated
in the U.S. was important to
her, and that's

39:57.028 --> 39:59.664 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
why they settled in Palomas.

39:59.697 --> 40:06.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROSA MARIA PRECIADO (through
translator):
I came to Palomas because of a
friend who

40:06.437 --> 40:10.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said Palomas would be a good
option to live
with my children.

40:10.475 --> 40:14.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is easy to cross into the
United States,
and there is a bus to take them
to school.

40:14.912 --> 40:20.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Armando Chavez
is the principal
of Columbus Elementary in Luna
County.

40:20.618 --> 40:25.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says the school district
usually sees an
influx of students when states
enact strict

40:25.757 --> 40:28.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
immigration laws, as Arizona did
in 2010.

40:28.793 --> 40:33.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARMANDO CHAVEZ, Principal,
Columbus Elementary:
We are sometimes the holding
spot for them,

40:33.131 --> 40:34.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for them to fix the papers
correctly.

40:34.899 --> 40:38.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are dealing with children
that come from
South Dakota, Missouri.

40:39.003 --> 40:44.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It can be any state that they
come, but we
embrace our children that come
to our door

40:44.108 --> 40:45.743 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
every day.

40:45.777 --> 40:50.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: School districts
in Texas
and California also allow
students living

40:50.348 --> 40:52.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in Mexico to come to school.

40:52.750 --> 40:56.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But they often charge
out-of-district fees
or are private.

40:56.120 --> 41:02.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the U.S. citizen-students
coming from
Palomas to school in Luna
County, the education

41:02.360 --> 41:05.863 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is free.

41:05.897 --> 41:11.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many teachers in the Luna County
schools crossed
the border as students.

41:11.302 --> 41:16.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ricardo Gutierrez teaches the
fifth grade
at Columbus Elementary, the
school he attended

41:16.841 --> 41:18.443 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as a child.

41:18.476 --> 41:23.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICARDO GUTIERREZ, Teacher: So
now it's my
turn to give back to the
community.

41:23.748 --> 41:27.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Gutierrez says
keeping parents
engaged in their children's
education is the

41:27.852 --> 41:29.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
biggest challenge.

41:29.420 --> 41:34.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He opens his restaurant in
Palomas for parent-teacher
conferences via Skype.

41:34.459 --> 41:42.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for this year's graduation
ceremony, he
hosted a live watch party for
parents that

41:42.367 --> 41:49.841 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
can't cross.

41:49.874 --> 41:54.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But not everybody living in the
Luna County
area thinks that state money
should be used

41:54.045 --> 41:56.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to educate students who don't
live in the
United States.

41:56.914 --> 41:58.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RUSS HOWELL, Chair, Republican
Party of Luna
County: They are getting a free
education.

41:59.016 --> 42:04.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Luna County
Republican Party
chair Russ Howell says
allowances like the

42:04.188 --> 42:09.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one being made by the school
district motivate
people to exploit birthright
citizenship.

42:09.594 --> 42:18.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RUSS HOWELL: They don't live in
the United
States, so that forces the state
of New Mexico

42:18.369 --> 42:25.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to pay for their education, as
well as those
of us that are taxed to pay for
them too.

42:25.076 --> 42:30.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: The New Mexico
State Constitution
requires public schools to be
open to all

42:30.481 --> 42:37.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the children of school age,
regardless of
residence.

42:37.855 --> 42:42.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Principal Chavez says, if there
are concerns
about students not paying their
fair share,

42:42.593 --> 42:45.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is more reason to make sure
they're getting
a good education.

42:45.696 --> 42:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARMANDO CHAVEZ: They are going
to more than
likely live in the United
States.

42:49.734 --> 42:51.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We want to educate them.

42:51.536 --> 42:55.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to get them to the
highest level of
education possible, so they can
be successful,

42:55.873 --> 42:59.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and so they can become
productive members
and contribute back.

42:59.777 --> 43:06.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Rosa Maria
Preciado says her
three oldest children are
already making their

43:06.150 --> 43:08.019 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
contributions.

43:08.052 --> 43:12.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her oldest daughter serves in
the U.S. military
and her two sons have careers in
engineering

43:12.790 --> 43:14.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and manufacturing.

43:14.592 --> 43:20.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROSA MARIA PRECIADO (through
translator):
I am very proud, because I have
a lot of family,

43:21.032 --> 43:25.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and almost none of their
children graduated
from anything, not even high
school.

43:25.870 --> 43:27.338 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I have two that graduated.

43:27.371 --> 43:29.507 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they have their careers.

43:29.540 --> 43:33.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That has made me really proud
and it has given
me a lot of happiness.

43:33.644 --> 43:39.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIMON THOMPSON: Lizett is
scheduled to graduate
next spring, and plans to study
engineering

43:39.150 --> 43:41.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at Colorado State.

43:41.619 --> 43:46.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Preciado hopes an immigration
pardon waiver
she is eligible for in two years
will allow

43:46.290 --> 43:49.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the whole family to reunite in
the U.S.

43:49.961 --> 43:51.796 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But there are no guarantees.

43:51.829 --> 44:00.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Simon Thompson
in Luna County, New Mexico.

44:00.638 --> 44:13.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We often think of
history as
words recorded in a textbooks,
but some of

44:13.184 --> 44:17.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the most powerful stories of our
past are
told through images.

44:17.388 --> 44:24.362 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As David C. Barnett from
WVIZ/PBS ideastream
in Cleveland reports, an exhibit
at the Maltz

44:24.395 --> 44:31.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Museum of Jewish documents a
crucial period
in the civil rights movement of
the 1960s

44:31.068 --> 44:34.906 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
through the work of nine
photographers.

44:34.939 --> 44:48.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Martin Luther
King Jr. led
about 25,000 people into
Montgomery, Alabama,

44:48.986 --> 44:54.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in March of 1965 as part of a
demonstration
to promote voting rights.

44:54.258 --> 44:58.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Government officials in several
Southern states
were trying to suppress the
African-American

44:58.462 --> 45:01.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
vote by making it difficult to
register.

45:01.566 --> 45:05.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Historian Leslie Kelen says a
rigged literacy
test often made it impossible.

45:05.236 --> 45:08.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LESLIE KELEN, Center for
Documentary Expression
and Art: White people who also
took the literacy

45:08.906 --> 45:12.810 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
test were almost always passed.

45:12.843 --> 45:15.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And about 98 percent of the
black people failed.

45:15.513 --> 45:20.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Kelen is
executive director
for the Utah-based Center for
Documentary

45:20.418 --> 45:25.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Expression and Art, which has
organized a
traveling photo exhibition which
tells the

45:25.389 --> 45:29.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
story of that voting rights
march and other
civil rights events of the
mid-1960s.

45:29.193 --> 45:35.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Currently on display at
Cleveland's Maltz
Museum of Jewish heritage, the
exhibition

45:35.166 --> 45:41.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gives a behind-the-scenes look
at everything
from quiet moments to violent
confrontations.

45:41.572 --> 45:47.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Montgomery demonstration
brings many memories
back to 81-year-old Otis Moss
Jr., who marched

45:47.845 --> 45:53.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with King and for 33 years was
pastor of Cleveland's
Olivet Institutional Baptist
Church.

45:54.018 --> 45:58.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Reverend Ross recalls that a
previous protest
had resulted in a vicious attack
by state

45:58.556 --> 46:02.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
troopers, so he had mixed
emotions as the
march approached the city.

46:02.293 --> 46:09.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OTIS MOSS JR., Former Pastor,
Olivet Institutional
Baptist Church: It was a great
moment of anticipation,

46:09.567 --> 46:16.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acknowledgment of the danger,
but also fully
aware of the necessity.

46:16.407 --> 46:21.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: As it turned
out, they walked
into Alabama's capital city
without incident,

46:21.379 --> 46:26.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thanks in part to the powerful
images of earlier
violence that were printed and
broadcast around

46:26.584 --> 46:28.552 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the world.

